<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><strong>Equations for Sphere, Cylinder, an=
d Cone Volume</strong> (Rade and Westergren, 1990)</p>

<p style=3D"text-align: center;"><img src=3D"https://www.lmnoeng.com/Volume=
/Cylinder%20Cone%20Sphere%20Equation.GIF" width=3D"457" height=3D"145" alt=
=3D"Partially full sphere, cylinder, cone equations"></p>

<p><strong>Discussion</strong><br><br>
This web page is designed to compute volumes of storage tanks for engineers=
 and=20
scientists; however, it may be useful to anyone who needs to know the volum=
e of a full or=20
partially full sphere, cylinder, or cone. Technically, our "cone" is not=20
really a cone; it is a "frustum of a right cone" (<a href=3D"https://www.lm=
noeng.com/Volume/CylConeSphere.php#References">Rade and=20
Westergren, 1990, p. 73</a>). A cone is a frustum that has a top diameter o=
f=20
0.0. For the cylinder laying on its side, if you enter liquid top width, di=
ameter,=20
and length, there are two possible solutions for depth and volume; therefor=
e, when using=20
the drop-down menu to select which calculation to perform, you must select =
whether the=20
cylinder is more or less than half full.</p>

<p><strong><br>Variables</strong><br><br>
D =3D Sphere or cylinder diameter [L].<br>
D<sub>bot</sub> =3D Cone bottom diameter [L].<br>
D<sub>top</sub> =3D Cone top diameter [L].<br>
h =3D Cone height [L].<br>
L =3D Cylinder length [L].<br>
T =3D Top width of liquid in cylinder [L].<br>
V =3D Volume of liquid in cylinder, cone, or sphere [L<sup>3</sup>].<br>
y =3D Liquid depth in sphere or cylinder [L].<br>
z =3D Horizontal to vertical side slope of cone.&nbsp; z&lt;0 if D<sub>top<=
/sub>&lt;D<sub>bot</sub>.&nbsp;=20
z=3D0 if D<sub>top</sub>=3DD<sub>bot</sub>.&nbsp; z&gt;0 if D<sub>top</sub>=
&gt;D<sub>bot</sub>.<br>
=CE=B8 =3D Angle representing how full the cylinder is [radians or degrees]=
.&nbsp; An empty=20
cylinder has =CE=B8=3D0<sup>o</sup>,&nbsp; a cylinder with =CE=B8=3D180<sup=
>o</sup> is half full, and=20
a cylinder with =CE=B8=3D360<sup>o</sup> is completely full.<br>
</p>

<p><br><strong>Error Messages</strong><br><br>
<em>"D must be &gt; 0."</em> Cylinder diameter was entered as =E2=89=A4 0; =
it=20
must be positive.<br>
<em>"D's must be =E2=89=A5 0."</em> D<sub>top</sub> or D<sub>bot</sub> for =
the=20
cone was entered as negative.<br>
<em>"h must be =E2=89=A5 0."</em> Cone height was entered as negative.<br>
<em>"L must be &gt; 0."</em> Cylinder length was entered as =E2=89=A4 0.<br=
>
<em>"T must be =E2=89=A5 0."</em> Cylinder top width was entered as negativ=
e.<br>
<em>"T must be =E2=89=A4 D."</em> Cylinder liquid top width cannot be great=
er=20
than cylinder diameter.<br>
<em>"y must be =E2=89=A5 0."</em> Sphere or cylinder liquid depth was enter=
ed=20
as negative.<br>
<em>"y must be =E2=89=A4 D."</em> Sphere or cylinder liquid depth cannot be=
=20
greater than diameter.<br>
<em>"Infeasible. D<sub>bot</sub> will be &lt; 0."</em> The slope that was=
=20
input for the cone gives a bottom diameter that is negative, which is physi=
cally=20
impossible. Most likely the slope was entered with an incorrect sign. Slope=
 is=20
Horizontal/Vertical and is negative for a cone with a smaller top than bott=
om.<br>
<em>"Infeasible. D<sub>top</sub> will be &lt; 0."</em> Similar to above.</p=
>

<p><br><strong>Reference</strong><br><br>
Rade, Lennart and Westergren, Bertil. 1990. Beta Mathematics Handbook. CRC =
Press. 2ed.</p>

